<!--
VOICING PLAN:
- The dotted-rhythm march feel drives the choice of crisp chord changes on half-bar
  boundaries — RH chords mostly in halves or quarters to match the rhythmic energy.
- E° (vii° in F major, diatonic) used in mm. 6 and 9 for harmonic color.
- Am (non-diatonic) substituted with Dm (vi) throughout — A and C notes fit both.
- Phrase 1 (mm. 1–4): Sparse but rhythmically clear. LH open "33" triads.
  m.4: descending scale passage (D5–C5–Bb4–A4) treated with half-bar chord changes.
- Phrase 2 (mm. 5–8): m.5 RH arpeggio adds momentum. m.7 LH gets its fullest 4-note
  voicing (Bb2-D3-F3-Bb3) — climax of this phrase. m.9 has 4 chords in one bar.
- Phrase 3 (mm. 9–12): Most rhythmically active (4 chords in m.9). m.11 has the
  widest range: RH reaches F5, LH 4-note chords, melody holds C5 for 2+ beats.
  Final V–I in m.12: RH 3-note triad, LH 4-note root pos.

VOICE LEADING HIGHLIGHTS:
- m.4 descending alto (RH upper): D5→C5→Bb4 mirrors the melody cascade.
- m.6 chromatic passing: E2–G2–Bb2 (vii°) → F2–C3 (I) — half-step bass resolution.
- m.9 bass walk: F2→C2→Bb2→E2 — each a diatonic step, contrary motion with soprano.
- m.11 widest reach: LH C2 to A3 (octave+6th), RH G4 to F5 (minor 7th).

TEXTURE ARC:
- mm. 1–4: Light entry — half-bar changes, 2-note RH, 3-note LH
- mm. 5–8: Building momentum — RH arpeggio, 4-note LH in m.7
- mm. 9–12: Climax refrain — 4 chords/bar in m.9, full 4-note LH/3-note RH
  Final cadence: 4-note LH root position, 3-note RH triad
-->
